pupils are dilated but reactive. He has dry mucous membranes. An ECG shows sinus tachycardia with a QRS duration of 160ms and a dominant R wave in aVR. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following agents is most likely responsible for his ECG changes?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Sertraline","Amitriptyline","Escitalopram","Venlafaxine","Quetiapine"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features of mixed drug overdose, with ECG changes characteristic of sodium channel blockade. The prolonged QRS duration and the dominant R wave in aVR are pathognomonic of tricyclic antidepressant toxicity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmitriptyline\u003C/strong\u003E is a tricyclic antidepressant that causes significant sodium channel blockade in overdose. This manifests as QRS prolongation, right axis deviation of the terminal QRS vector, and hypotension. Treatment involves sodium bicarbonate administration to overcome the sodium channel blockade.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESertraline\u003C/strong\u003E is a selective serotonin reuptake inhibitor (SSRI) that rarely causes significant cardiovascular toxicity in overdose. While it can cause serotonin syndrome, it does not typically cause ECG changes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVenlafaxine\u003C/strong\u003E is a serotonin-noradrenaline reuptake inhibitor (SNRI) that can cause seizures and serotonin syndrome in overdose. While it can cause QT prolongation, it does not typically cause significant QRS prolongation or sodium channel blockade.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EQuetiapine\u003C/strong\u003E is an atypical antipsychotic that primarily causes sedation and anticholinergic effects in overdose. While it can cause QT prolongation, it does not typically cause significant sodium channel blockade.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEscitalopram\u003C/strong\u003E is an SSRI that can cause QT prolongation in overdose but does not typically cause significant sodium channel blockade or QRS prolongation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Sodium channel blockade from tricyclic antidepressant overdose presents with QRS prolongation and a dominant R wave in aVR (terminal right axis deviation).","Tricyclic antidepressants are highly toxic in overdose due to their sodium channel blocking properties.","Treatment of significant tricyclic overdose includes sodium bicarbonate to overcome sodium channel blockade."],"references":["Body R, Bartram T, Azam F, et al. Guidelines in Emergency Medicine Network (GEMNet): guideline for the management of tricyclic antidepressant overdose. Emerg Med J. 2011;28:347-368.","Khalid MM, Waseem M. Tricyclic Antidepressant Toxicity. [Updated 2023 Jul 17]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK430931/","Dokken K, Chen RJ, Fairley P. Sodium Channel Blocker Toxicity. [Updated 2024 Mar 2]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK534844/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42660"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14593"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42660","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/42660"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-25T11:52:22+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-25T11:52:53+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7286"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57201"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":n